# Optimal Code (Python)

```python
class Solution:
    def increasingNumbers(self, n):

        if n > 10:
            return []

        if n == 1:
            return list(range(10))

        ans = []

        def dfs(num, last_digit, length):

            if length == n:
                ans.append(num)
                return

            for digit in range(last_digit + 1, 10):
                dfs(num * 10 + digit, digit, length + 1)

        for start in range(1, 10):
            dfs(start, start, 1)

        return ans
```

---

# Time Complexity

The algorithm generates only valid numbers.

Number of valid numbers

```
C(9,n)
```

Building each number

```
O(n)
```

Overall

```
O(C(9,n) × n)
```

Since there are only 10 digits, the total number of valid outputs is bounded by a small constant (at most 1023 across all lengths), making this effectively constant-time for practical purposes.

---

# Space Complexity

Recursion depth

```
O(n)
```

Output array

```
O(C(9,n))
```

Ignoring output

```
O(n)
```

