# Comparison

| Feature | Brute Force | Optimal |
|----------|------------|----------|
| Generate all numbers | ✅ | ❌ |
| Generate only valid numbers | ❌ | ✅ |
| Extra Checking | High | None |
| Time Complexity | O(10^n × n) | O(C(9,n) × n) |
| Space Complexity | O(1) | O(n) |
| Efficient | ❌ | ✅ |

---

# Key Takeaways

- Brute Force generates every possible n-digit number and checks validity.
- Backtracking generates only valid increasing numbers.
- Digits never repeat.
- Digits are chosen in increasing order.
- If `n > 10`, the answer is always empty because only 10 distinct digits exist.

